<div id="review_2058302975" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2058302975" />
    <a title="Edward" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12933866-edward"><img alt="Edward" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1444136022p2/12933866.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2058302975?book_show_action=true">Feb 18, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Edward" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Edward" href="/user/show/12933866-edward">Edward</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781860460197" href="/book/show/1340992.Life_and_Fate">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12933866-edward?shelf=2019">2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12933866-edward?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12933866-edward?shelf=literary-fiction">literary-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2058302975" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3704645839176166265">I&apos;m lucky to have been born in 1980 and not 1920. Because of this simple fact, I will never have to face an opposing army with a pistol pointed at me from behind, to die in machine-gun fire, or be standing in the wrong place when a bomb is dropped. I won&apos;t be killed in a gas chamber, my body searched for gold and burned, or be made to lie on a pile of dead bodies awaiting a bullet to my head, or be sent to prison camp, subjected to beatings and forced into hard labour. I will never have to endur</span>
  <span id="freeText3704645839176166265" style="display:none">I'm lucky to have been born in 1980 and not 1920. Because of this simple fact, I will never have to face an opposing army with a pistol pointed at me from behind, to die in machine-gun fire, or be standing in the wrong place when a bomb is dropped. I won't be killed in a gas chamber, my body searched for gold and burned, or be made to lie on a pile of dead bodies awaiting a bullet to my head, or be sent to prison camp, subjected to beatings and forced into hard labour. I will never have to endure real hunger, have my family or my property taken away from me, to live in fear of being denounced. I will not be treated as subhuman because of my race. <br /><br />What separates the world today from the horrors of that time? There is greater economic prosperity, more education, perhaps more compassion and tolerance. We have the wisdom of recent memory to remind us what we must avoid. But these are differences in external conditions; our underlying human nature remains unchanged. What would it take to find ourselves once again in 1942: a clash between major powers, a global climate catastrophe, growing inequality, religious violence, overpopulation, economic turmoil caused by automation or artificial intelligence? The seeds are visible. The challenges of this century may be even greater than the last, and the way we continually respond to these challenges defines the kind of society we will live in. We must never complacently believe that history is complete, something that has been accomplished for the benefit of those lucky enough to be living today. We continue to live in history and shape the world of the future. A novel like <i>Life and Fate</i> is a powerful reminder of the evil we can inflict upon ourselves, of how impossibly far we are capable of falling. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3704645839176166265" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


