    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1664527478" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1664527478" />
    <a title="Roman Clodia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/56111743-roman-clodia"><img alt="Roman Clodia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1464021031p2/56111743.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1664527478?book_show_action=true">Oct 16, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Roman Clodia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Roman Clodia" href="/user/show/56111743-roman-clodia">Roman Clodia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1664527478" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12977700998282079239"><i>
  <blockquote>In every word the two sisters said, in all the sad, joyful, absurd or touching events they related, they could sense the presence of friends and family who had died but who would always be bound to them.</blockquote>
</i><br/>There&apos;s no question that the scope of this book is immense and Grossman does a magnificent job of keeping tags on his vast cast of characters: from Russian pilots and tank- men to snipers and the workers keeping the power station at Stalingrad working; from General Paulus and the Germans to H</span>
  <span id="freeText12977700998282079239" style="display:none"><i>
  <blockquote>In every word the two sisters said, in all the sad, joyful, absurd or touching events they related, they could sense the presence of friends and family who had died but who would always be bound to them.</blockquote>
</i><br />There's no question that the scope of this book is immense and Grossman does a magnificent job of keeping tags on his vast cast of characters: from Russian pilots and tank- men to snipers and the workers keeping the power station at Stalingrad working; from General Paulus and the Germans to Hitler and Stalin; from Soviet commissars to so-called dissidents in the Lubyanka; from doctors and nurses working in war-time conditions, to Russian Jews being transported on their last journey to the crematoria. <br /><br />There are scenes which stand out (the gassing of a trainload of Jewish prisoners), there are mini-essays on 'freedom' and anti-Semitism, there are fragments of lives: Zhenya being torn between two men, a mother's journey to find her son wounded and in hospital, a physicist getting a call from Stalin himself. But, like his Stalingrad, I found this a magnificent failure as a novel. Grossman writes like a journalist not a novelist: his characters don't really have characters, they're the embodiment of situations (the daughter in love with and pregnant by a young pilot, the young woman alone with a besieged group of Russian soldiers who becomes to Juliet to a young Romeo, the ambitious tank commander who turns out to be unlucky in love). Stories are started and then almost dismissed: <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Victorov's death, for example: we never return to find out how Vera learns of it <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />It's not just the personal stories which get a bit lost in the panorama, it's also that I never really got a sense of fighting, not even at the height of the battle for Stalingrad. Planes fly, tanks advance, snipers snipe (or whatever they do), but it's not visceral. <br /><br />This feels more like a vast panorama which focuses in on a scene or a group before the spotlight moves on. It certainly captures a sense of Soviet Russia: it's notable how politicised all the characters are: they're conscious of fighting Fascism, for example, not just the Germans as sometimes feels the case from reading British war literature. <br /><br />For such a long book, this is a surprisingly fast read as the short chapters and constant switching of scenes mean that I powered through this effortlessly. It's bold and consistently interesting, but at times I wanted more depth in character or attachment to events. For a near-contemporary account of what Stalingrad meant to Russians this is probably unsurpassable. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12977700998282079239" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


