    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_85918227" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/85918227" />
    <a title="Chrissie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie"><img alt="Chrissie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1321799585p2/632247.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/85918227?book_show_action=true">Jun 06, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chrissie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chrissie" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie">Chrissie</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=ww2">ww2</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=2019-read">2019-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=politics">politics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=long">long</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=russia">russia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=hf">hf</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=soviet-union">soviet-union</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=audible-uk">audible-uk</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=bio">bio</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer85918227" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18356144851311882358">I cannot rate this book. <br/><br/>I have listened to BBC Radio Four’s eight-hour dramatization of <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/88432.Life_and_Fate' title='Life and Fate by Vasily Grossman' rel='nofollow noopener'>Life and Fate</a> by <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/19595.Vasily_Grossman' title='Vasily Grossman' rel='nofollow noopener'>Vasily Grossman</a>. It is available at Audible. I cannot properly judge <u>the book</u> because I am unsure to what extent the prose has been altered in the audio version. I must make the assumption that parts have been cut. <br/><br/>I had difficulty keeping track of the story’s numerous characters. The German names were not difficult, but the Russian ones were. The sound effects all too often prevented me fro</span>
  <span id="freeText18356144851311882358" style="display:none">I cannot rate this book. <br /><br />I have listened to BBC Radio Four’s eight-hour dramatization of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/88432.Life_and_Fate" title="Life and Fate by Vasily Grossman" rel="nofollow noopener">Life and Fate</a> by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/19595.Vasily_Grossman" title="Vasily Grossman" rel="nofollow noopener">Vasily Grossman</a>. It is available at Audible. I cannot properly judge <u>the book</u> because I am unsure to what extent the prose has been altered in the audio version. I must make the assumption that parts have been cut. <br /><br />I had difficulty keeping track of the story’s numerous characters. The German names were not difficult, but the Russian ones were. The sound effects all too often prevented me from hearing dialogues. Much of the story is set in Stalingrad 1942 and the beginning of 1943. The fight for Stalingrad is central to the story. The author was a war correspondent during the Great Patriotic War, and he covered the battle for Stalingrad. Bombing, explosions and screams or the slamming of doors, sobs and whispering made it difficult for me to catch every word. <br /><br />The book is set not only in Stalingrad. Kazan and Moscow and Stalin’s gulags are other settings. Also, Nazi concentration camps. The totalitarian regimes of both Hitler and Stalin are compared. Both are deplored. This is clearly Vasily Grossman’s central message.<br /><br />He speaks also of the ravages of war, and the masses who suffer as a result of them. He stresses the value of freedom. The author was himself a Ukrainian Jew. There are many elements of the story that resemble events of his own life. The death of his mother mirrors the death of the book’s central character’s mother. I am very glad to have read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/3118188.Alexandra_Popoff" title="Alexandra Popoff" rel="nofollow noopener">Alexandra Popoff</a>’s <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41154989.Vasily_Grossman_and_the_Soviet_Century" title="Vasily Grossman and the Soviet Century by Alexandra Popoff" rel="nofollow noopener">Vasily Grossman and the Soviet Century</a> first. This helped me understand and interpret the story’s events. <br /><br /><u>Life and Fate</u> is considered the author’s magnus opus. It is worth reading for this reason alone. It is a sequel to the author’s <u>For a Just Cause</u>, which was published in 1952 under Stalin’s rule. However, while the prequel expresses loyalty to Stalin’s regime, it had to be so or it would not have been allowed to be published, <u>Life and Fate</u> criticizes Stalin, and Hitler too! Personally, I prefer reading that book which expresses the author’s true sentiments rather than the prequel which has been altered to enable publication. <u>For a Just Cause</u> has recently been made available in English under the title <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41087239.Stalingrad" title="Stalingrad by Vasily Grossman" rel="nofollow noopener">Stalingrad</a>. <br /><br />The story of how <u>Life and Fate</u> came to be published is interesting and is covered in Popoff’s book. <u>Life and Fate</u>, written in the 1950s, was completed in 1960. It was considered so dangerous that the KGB stole the manuscript. It has in this respect been compared to <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/7902.Boris_Pasternak" title="Boris Pasternak" rel="nofollow noopener">Boris Pasternak</a>'s <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/130440.Doctor_Zhivago" title="Doctor Zhivago by Boris Pasternak" rel="nofollow noopener">Doctor Zhivago</a>. A microfilmed copy was smuggled out of the country in 1974. In the West it came out in print first in 1980. Not until 1988 was it published n Russia.<br /><br />Listening to almost eight hours was draining. There is so much violence, given the war scenes, Nazi camps, Stalin’s camps and the beatings in Moscow’s Lubyanka prison—particularly with the added, terrifying, dramatized sound effects. I should add that there are love scenes. In war people have a need to reach out to each other. Also in war, soldiers do tend to speak vulgarly of women and sex to each other. I have added this as a word of warning. The sound of the clipping of scissors is horrifying when prisoners’ hair is cut on entrance to Nazi camps. <br /><br />That is it. I have said enough. I do not know whether to recommend this to others. It all depends on what you are looking for and what you can cope with.<br /> <br /><br />******************<br /><br /><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41154989.Vasily_Grossman_and_the_Soviet_Century" title="Vasily Grossman and the Soviet Century by Alexandra Popoff" rel="nofollow noopener">Vasily Grossman and the Soviet Century</a> 3 stars by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/3118188.Alexandra_Popoff" title="Alexandra Popoff" rel="nofollow noopener">Alexandra Popoff</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="18356144851311882358" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


