  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2810792557" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2810792557" />
    <a title="Bob Brinkmeyer" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/34401683-bob-brinkmeyer"><img alt="Bob Brinkmeyer" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1580600423p2/34401683.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2810792557?book_show_action=true">Jul 13, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bob Brinkmeyer" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bob Brinkmeyer" href="/user/show/34401683-bob-brinkmeyer">Bob Brinkmeyer</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2810792557" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13247722071232085057">I’m no expert on literature of World War II, but Life and Fate must be one of the world’s greatest novels of that war. Frequently compared to War and Peace (particularly when combined with its recently-published prequel, Stalingrad), Life and Fate is epic in scope and depth, portraying a world of characters (thankfully there’s an 8-page appendix listing important characters to help you keep everybody straight) and numerous storylines, many of which in some way touch upon one extended family. The</span>
  <span id="freeText13247722071232085057" style="display:none">I’m no expert on literature of World War II, but Life and Fate must be one of the world’s greatest novels of that war. Frequently compared to War and Peace (particularly when combined with its recently-published prequel, Stalingrad), Life and Fate is epic in scope and depth, portraying a world of characters (thankfully there’s an 8-page appendix listing important characters to help you keep everybody straight) and numerous storylines, many of which in some way touch upon one extended family. The battle of Stalingrad is everywhere present, either at the center of the action (there are a number of harrowing battle scenes) or as the backdrop—no matter how far from the battle, everyone knows that the fate of the war is hanging in the balance and everyone is affected by war’s demands and sufferings. Grossman presents a vast panorama of the Soviet Union at war, taking the reader into a host of Soviet towns and cities where everyday life has unraveled, often into chaos, as well as into Lubyanka prison, a Siberian labor camp, a Nazi death camp, a Jewish ghetto, a German POW camp, and a laboratory investigating nuclear fission. <br /><br />The crushing tensions that shape the novel focus less on the large-scale battle between the Nazis and the Soviets (we know who wins) and more on the smaller (but, as novel underscores, no less important) struggles of individuals to maintain humanity and dignity, often in situations that demand otherwise. This is the tension of the novel’s title: that between what is fated to people—the totalitarian society in which they live, the war in which they find themselves, for instance—and the efforts at staying alive, literally and emotionally/individually (in the sense of remaining an individual and not merely a cog in the machine). As Grossman makes clear throughout the novel, this is rarely a simple either/or choice; unless a person is a saint, his or her life is a complicated mix of will, compromise, and betrayal. Or as Grossman describes the life of one of the Nazis in the novel: “Every step that Kaltluft had taken—from the village to the trenches, from being a man-in-the-street to being a member of the Nationalist Socialist Party—bore the imprint of his will. A man may be led by fate, but he can refuse to follow. He may be a mere tool in the hands of destructive powers, but he knows it is in his interest to assent to this. Fate and the individual may have different ends, but they share the same path.”<br /><br />The assertion of life amidst crushing fate (particularly the crushing power of totalitarianism) is often seen in characters striving to find, remain loyal to, and hold onto love and loved ones. At one point one of the characters characterizes this commitment to love as the commitment to irrational kindness, what he sees as the basic kernel of humanity: “The powerlessness of kindness, of senseless kindness, is the secret of its immortality. It can never be conquered. The more stupid, the more senseless, the more helpless it may seem, the vaster it is. Evil is impotent before it. The prophets, religious teachers, reformers, social and political leaders are impotent before it. This dumb, blind love is man’s meaning.” It is by a similar line of thinking that another character, also aware of the goodness buried in the depths of consciousness, describes death as a passing from freedom into slavery: “Life is freedom, and dying is a gradual denial of freedom. Consciousness first weakens and then disappears. The life-processes—respiration, the metabolism, the circulation—continue for some time, but an irrevocable move has been made towards slavery; consciousness, the flame of freedom, has died out.”<br /><br />I am quoting so much because this is such a powerful, frightening, and yet finally inspiring novel, particularly for readers in these dark days when so many things seem to be coming unhinged, not the least being our very world and its climate. I’ll end with one more quotation, for me the most powerful passage in the novel, a passage that underscores that hopefulness in Grossman’s world is anything but a saccharine glossing over of the destructive power of evil and despair: “And here she was, an old woman now, living and hoping, keeping faith, afraid of evil, full of anxiety for the living and an equal concern for the dead; here she was, looking at the ruins of her home, admiring the spring sky without knowing that she was admiring it, wondering why the future of those she loved was so obscure and the past so full of mistakes, not realizing that this very obscurity and unhappiness concealed a strange hope and clarity, not realizing that in the depths of her soul she already the meaning of both her own life and the lives of her nearest and dearest, not realizing that even though neither she herself nor any of them could tell what was in store, even though they all knew only too well that at times like these no man can forge his own happiness and that fate alone has the power to pardon and chastise, to raise up to glory and to plunge into need, to reduce a man to labour-camp dust, nevertheless neither fate, nor history, nor the anger of the State, nor the glory or infamy of battle has any power to affect those who call themselves human beings. No, whatever life holds in store—hard-won glory, poverty and despair, or death in a labour-camp—they will live as human beings and die as human beings, the same as those who have already perished; and in this alone lies man’s eternal and bitter victory over all the grandiose and inhuman forces that ever have been or will be.”</span>
  <a data-text-id="13247722071232085057" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

